To control the size of images in Markdown, follow these steps:

1. Use an image reference with a width and height attribute: For example, include `width` and `height` attributes within your HTML tag for images (e.g., `<img src="image.jpg" alt="" width="200px" height="150px">`).

2. Use CSS to control the size of images: Apply CSS rules targeting image elements with a specific class or ID, such as:
```.css
  img {
    max-width: 100%;
    height: auto; /* Maintain aspect ratio */
  }
}
.responsive-image {
  width: 300px;
  height: 200px;
}
```
In your Markdown, reference the image with a class or ID attribute (e.g., `![Alt text](/path/to/img.jpg "Title"){: .responsive-image }`).

3. Use HTML5 figures and captions: Wrap your images in a figure element and add caption attributes to control the size of images with captions (e.g., `<figure><img src="/path/to/img.jpg" alt="Alternative text" width="200px" height="150px"> <figcaption>Caption</figcaption></figure>`).

Remember to place these code snippets in your Markdown file, usually within the YAML Front Matter or at the beginning of the document.

